10:51.000 --> 11:07.000
During the past few weeks, I have received a great many letters from constituents and people in Tennessee asking that I explain something about the drug inquiry, which the Senate Committee of Ponmanopoli and Antitrust, of which I'm chairman is presently conducting.

11:07.000 --> 11:11.000
And I'm welcoming this opportunity of doing so.

11:11.000 --> 11:15.000
This Committee of which I'm chairman has been in existence for a number of years.

11:15.000 --> 11:26.000
We are charged with the responsibility of investigating monopoly lack of competition in order to try to see that we do not have cartels and monopolization.

11:26.000 --> 11:35.000
Also to try to see that the small businessman has a chance and that the consumer in the case of drugs, the patient gets a break too.

11:35.000 --> 11:42.000
And of course, if our investigation we have investigated steel, oil, automobile, electrical equipment and many many other things.

11:42.000 --> 11:50.000
And there was a demand that there be some investigation of the manufacturer's price, the big manufacturer's price of drugs.

11:50.000 --> 11:56.000
I think we received a great deal more mail on this than we did all the other investigations put together.

11:56.000 --> 12:08.000
Indeed, a number of other senators in congressmen were interested in investigation as a matter of fact, senators smathers while the resolution asking it he be authorized to make an investigation.

12:08.000 --> 12:12.000
But we have been collecting material for some time.

12:12.000 --> 12:17.000
Now let me tell you just what we are trying to do.

12:17.000 --> 12:26.000
In the first place I want to make it very, very clear that this as in other cases is only investigation of at the manufacturer's level.

12:26.000 --> 12:37.000
We are not undertaking to get into the retail investigation of retail pharmacists or drug stores or wholesalers or anybody else.

12:37.000 --> 12:42.000
As a matter of fact, the retail pharmacist is entitled to make a reasonable profit.

12:42.000 --> 12:47.000
His profit is less than it is in the good many other lands of industry.

12:47.000 --> 12:55.000
And by virtue of the fact that he has to carry such a large inventory of trade names, this doesn't increase his cost.

12:55.000 --> 12:59.000
We have the cooperation of a great many pharmacist I'm happy to say.

12:59.000 --> 13:12.000
I'm sorry to say however that some seem to be letting the pharmacists take the blame for what should be the what is the blame of the large pharmaceutical manufacturers.

13:12.000 --> 13:22.000
When they get complaints about prices at the retail level, they simply explain that they have to pay higher prices to the manufacturer for these products.

13:22.000 --> 13:30.000
The second thing is that the physician is very much interested in the well fair economic welfare of his patient.

13:30.000 --> 13:35.000
For the first time in history the cost of drugs has exceeded the cost of medical care.

13:35.000 --> 13:44.000
Very often a physician will charge say $5 for a visit. The prescription may cost $9 or $9.5.

13:44.000 --> 13:54.000
And the physician knows of course that his patient can get better treatment. You can get more of these good wonder drugs if the prices are lowered.

13:54.000 --> 14:04.000
Now let's see just and the wholesaler also in the drug field is we're not investigating him and we're not blaming him.

14:04.000 --> 14:11.000
Because he only guess a 15% differential which is little enough for him to try to do business on.

14:11.000 --> 14:21.000
All of these are entitled a fair profit, a fair return and we're not fussing about that. We want the big manufacturers to get a fair profit too.

14:21.000 --> 14:24.000
But we don't want them to charge excessive prices to people.

14:24.000 --> 14:35.000
Here are the high profit industries in the United States. In 1957 was a typical year in 1958. It's about the same only drug to maybe be a little more.

14:35.000 --> 14:45.000
You will see that after taxes, after payment for all of research and everything else the drug industry averaged almost 22% on net worth.

14:45.000 --> 14:51.000
The average for all manufacturing was just about 11% and you see some of the others.

14:51.000 --> 14:55.000
Well let me show you something about prices.

14:55.000 --> 15:06.000
In the case of a prednisone which is a card-son product used for the treatment of the 11 million arthritic people who must have these pills in the United States,

15:06.000 --> 15:14.000
the big companies charged the pharmacist is done at the same price as 17 and 9 cents per pill.

15:14.000 --> 15:20.000
But the little companies who meet food and drug standards and qualifications charge a whole lot less.

15:20.000 --> 15:25.000
They charge the government a whole lot less. We all in favor of research.

15:25.000 --> 15:30.000
But the research is only about 6.5% or 7% and can account for these high prices.

15:30.000 --> 15:38.000
We hope we'll have more time to talk about this investigation later on. Thank you very much.

