Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, Senate within the past week took action on two bills of importance.

20:40.000 --> 20:51.000
The first was the so-called Clean Elections Bill. After a number of amendments were adopted on the floor, this bill was passed, vote of 59 to 22 and went to the House of Representatives.

20:51.000 --> 20:57.000
The bill strengthens the requirement for reporting of campaign expenditures in quite a number of ways.

20:57.000 --> 21:03.000
It places a $10,000 limit on the amount any individual can contribute to any campaign.

21:03.000 --> 21:12.000
It requires reporting of campaign contributions in connection with primaries, as well as general elections involving federal officers.

21:12.000 --> 21:20.000
It requires reports from states and local committees spending more than $2,500 for the benefit of federal candidates.

21:20.000 --> 21:32.000
It also provides the detailed financial statements be filed with federal district courts, where they will be available to the press of the various states, as well as with the clerks of the House and of the Senate.

21:32.000 --> 21:42.000
The bill makes campaigns spending limitations more realistic and puts teeth on a law which has been for all practical purposes, loosely drawn and largely ignored.

21:43.000 --> 21:51.000
An amendment that I introduced did not pass. I reintroduced this in the form of a bill and hope that further consideration may be given it.

21:51.000 --> 22:05.000
My amendment was designed to encourage small contributions to campaigns by a much larger number of citizens. It would permit a $10 tax credit or $100 tax deduction for campaign contributions.

22:05.000 --> 22:16.000
Turning to another subject in the field of juvenile delinquency, the Senate passed the bill, which would provide grants to the states for study demonstration projects on a nationwide scale.

22:16.000 --> 22:24.000
The bill would also provide funds over the next five years for the training of personnel to work in the juvenile delinquency field.

22:24.000 --> 22:29.000
Juvenile delinquency, as we all know, is one of the most serious major problems in the nation today.

22:30.000 --> 22:42.000
It has been steadily increasing for the past ten years. A few communities have escaped this impact, and it can no longer be thought of as being confined within the boundaries of neighborhoods, local communities, or even states.

22:42.000 --> 22:52.000
The effects of juvenile delinquency are violent, disrespect for human value, and property value, and a more dangerous weakening of our moral structure in our society.

22:52.000 --> 23:00.000
I'm happy that the Senate has taken this positive step toward attacking this problem, and hopeful that the House will concur in the action.

23:00.000 --> 23:04.000
I was happy to be a sponsor along with Senator Hennings of this legislation.

23:04.000 --> 23:13.000
As I make this broadcast to you in Tennessee, the Senate is debating a constitutional amendment, which I have proposed.

23:13.000 --> 23:21.000
This amendment would empower the governors of several states to fill vacancies in the House of Representatives in case of a nuclear attack on Washington.

23:21.000 --> 23:26.000
Several attempts have been made in the past to get similar amendments passed, but they have failed.

23:26.000 --> 23:32.000
I'm hopeful the Senate and the House will pass it this time with resounding majorities.

23:32.000 --> 23:42.000
I believe the amendment is more urgently needed today than ever before. It would plug a loophole in our Constitution, which could not have been foreseen by our founding fathers.

23:43.000 --> 23:52.000
If a nuclear attack should occur in heaven forbid that it should, it is almost certain that a large number of congressmen would be killed or fatally wounded.

23:52.000 --> 24:00.000
Under the law is it now stands only the House of Representatives could not be quickly reconstituted after a devastating attack.

24:00.000 --> 24:05.000
Vacancies in the judicial branch and in the Senate could be filled by appointment.

24:06.000 --> 24:13.000
A long line of succession is provided by the Constitution and federal statutes for the Office of Chief Executive.

24:13.000 --> 24:18.000
Vacancies in the House of Representatives can be filled only by election of the people.

24:18.000 --> 24:31.000
If a nuclear attack were to wipe out half of our congressmen, it would be vital that the government get back in action as quickly as possible and the House could not act if a point of no quorum remained on the first date.

24:31.000 --> 24:38.000
The Prime Amendment would enable the governors to appoint vacancies in the House of Representatives for a period of 60 days only.

24:38.000 --> 24:43.000
The primary argument against this amendment is that it is born out of fear and panic.

24:43.000 --> 24:53.000
To me this is the same as saying that a husband should never buy life insurance or fear of frightening his wife or that a parent should not have his child vaccinated for fear of frightening the child.

24:53.000 --> 25:04.000
I am working hard for the adoption of this amendment SJRAS 39 and hope we will be able to amend the Constitution to take out this serious loophole.

25:04.000 --> 25:10.000
That's all for this time. Thank you and goodbye until next week.

